    "summary": "The Sino-Indian War was fought in October and November 1962 along disputed border territories in the Himalayas, principally in the Aksai Chin region claimed by both China and India, and in the Northeast Frontier Agency (now Arunachal Pradesh). The war resulted in a decisive Chinese military victory. Indian forces, poorly equipped and organized for high-altitude combat, suffered significant defeats. China declared a unilateral ceasefire in November 1962 and withdrew to positions it had held prior to the conflict, retaining control of Aksai Chin.\n\nThe conflict emerged from competing territorial claims stemming from colonial-era demarcations, particularly the McMahon Line drawn during British administration, which China rejected, and Chinese maps that included Aksai Chin as Chinese territory. Prime Minister Nehru's forward policy of establishing Indian posts in disputed areas created the immediate context for Chinese military response. The war shattered the spirit of Sino-Indian friendship that had characterized the early post-independence relationship, and border tensions between the two countries have persisted into the twenty-first century.\n\nThe defeat had profound consequences for India. It severely damaged Nehru's political standing and accelerated military modernization efforts. Defense spending increased substantially. The conflict also reshaped India's foreign policy orientation, increasing its distance from China and strengthening the case for closer security cooperation with outside powers.",
